    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:0ff0d9f2-deb6-4621-aa3f-5cdf38fa75ba",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 71-year-old woman from the Czech Republic who has recently become more tired and less active, describing a steady decline in stamina and a reduced ability to eat much at one sitting, with progressive weakness over the last several weeks [MEDDIALOG:C18.9:2]. She has also noticed intermittent unexplained bruising on her thighs in the past, which made her worry about cancer because of a strong family history of malignancy [MEDDIALOG:C18.9:1]. Her appearance is that of an older adult who is alert and cooperative but looks fatigued, with a cautious gait and concern about her health.\n\nShe is retired from office work and lives with her husband, spending much of her time helping with household routines, gardening in warmer months, and speaking regularly with her adult daughter by phone. Lately she has cut back on these activities because of her weakness and poor endurance [MEDDIALOG:C18.9:2]. She still tries to maintain social contact with a few close friends, but her recent symptoms have made her more withdrawn and anxious.\n\nIn conversation, {patientName} is practical and somewhat stoic, but she is increasingly worried by how little she can manage at meals and by her generalized weakness [MEDDIALOG:C18.9:2]. She denies dramatic acute complaints and instead describes a gradual change that has begun to affect her daily routines. Her main goal is to understand the cause of her decline and whether treatment can help.\n\nHer family relationships are important to her, and cancer has shaped her health concerns because multiple relatives have died from malignancy, including one with colon cancer [MEDDIALOG:C18.9:1]. That family history has made her attentive to new symptoms and motivated to follow through with testing and specialist evaluation."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:941c8848-219a-4068-92bd-3fe7557016a3",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
